		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">How many tiles editors does allow to edit graphics with a NTSC or PAL filter in mind ??</div><br />Videomation.<br /><br />But seriously: Once I planned to make an NES game including a tile editor that runs directly on the NES. I imagine that development systems by sometime in the later NES era included graphics creation systems somehow connected to the NES. I'd have made a tile editor and nametable editor for NES (SNROM) just for the sake of live preview, except the controller input is so limiting. If only I could buy a cable to plug Super NES controllers into an NES, then I could mouse around this.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">but other than that they probably didn't "design" graphics with NTSC display in mind.</div>
<br />Except for the general guideline to use a lot of random dots and thin odd-angle lines in random places to get a bit of additional texture from artifact colors as a pixel hits a different phase of the subcarrier period. Compare all the Genesis games that used 1px vertical stripes (1px there = 8/15 of a subcarrier period) to fool the VDP into making rainbows.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
