		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It's true the modern NES games (such as Batman ROTJ) looks better with NTSC while older NES games (such as Kid Icarus) looks way better with no filter.</div>
<br />Sunsoft sure were the masters of art and shading.  At one point (late 80s/early 90s) they did in fact use graphics/map layout tools running on Famicoms.  Other companies at the same time (Nintendo, Bandai, Toshiba EMI, others) used Fujitsu/NEC computers equipped with above-average graphics hardware and pixel-editing software. <a href="http://www.chrismcovell.com/secret/FC__1988Q2.html#ryoma" class="postlink">(Link)</a> And of course back in the Kid Icarus days, Nintendo probably used a lot of grid paper and felt-tip pens too.
<br />
<br />Well, anyway, the technology used for making Fami games ran the gamut.

		

